# Project Rules for Sire22 Explorer

# TanStack Query + Firebase Rules

## Project Architecture
- **Frontend:** React + Vite + TypeScript
- **UI:** shadcn/ui + Tailwind CSS
- **Data Fetching:** TanStack Query (React Query)
- **Backend:** Firebase (Auth + Firestore)
- **State Management:** Local state (useState/useReducer) + TanStack Query cache
- **No Zustand/Redux** (keep it simple for AI)

## TanStack Query Patterns

### Data Fetching
- Use `useQuery` for all GET operations
- Use `useMutation` for all POST/PUT/DELETE operations
- Always provide a `queryKey` array
- Set `staleTime` to avoid unnecessary refetches

### Example
```typescript
// ✅ Correct
const { data, isLoading } = useQuery({
  queryKey: ['users', userId],
  queryFn: () => getUserById(userId),
  staleTime: 1000 * 60 * 5, // 5 minutes
});

const mutation = useMutation({
  mutationFn: updateUser,
  onSuccess: () => {
    queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['users'] });
  },
});

Firebase + Firestore Patterns
Repository Pattern
Create repository files in src/lib/repositories/

Each collection gets its own repository

Repository handles all Firestore operations

Components call repositories, never Firebase directly

Structure

src/lib/repositories/
├── userRepository.ts
├── productRepository.ts
└── orderRepository.ts

Example Repository

// userRepository.ts
import { doc, getDoc, updateDoc, onSnapshot } from 'firebase/firestore';
import { db } from '../firebase';

export const userRepository = {
  async getById(id: string) {
    const docSnap = await getDoc(doc(db, 'users', id));
    return { id: docSnap.id, ...docSnap.data() };
  },
  
  subscribe(id: string, callback: (user: User) => void) {
    return onSnapshot(doc(db, 'users', id), (snap) => {
      callback({ id: snap.id, ...snap.data() });
    });
  }
};

Custom Hooks
Create hooks that use repositories

Use useQuery for query hooks

Use useMutation for update hooks

Name hooks: useUsers, useUser, useUpdateUser

Example Hook
// hooks/useUser.ts
export const useUser = (userId: string) => {
  return useQuery({
    queryKey: ['users', userId],
    queryFn: () => userRepository.getById(userId),
    enabled: !!userId,
  });
};

Error Handling
Use isError and error from TanStack Query

Show user-friendly error messages with shadcn/ui components

Log errors for debugging
const { data, isLoading, isError, error } = useQuery({
  queryKey: ['products'],
  queryFn: productRepository.getAll,
});

if (isError) {
  return <Alert variant="destructive">{error.message}</Alert>;
}

Real-time Subscriptions
Use Firebase onSnapshot for real-time data

Use useEffect to set up subscriptions

Clean up subscriptions in return function

Consider using useQuery with enabled for polling when needed
useEffect(() => {
  const unsubscribe = userRepository.subscribe(userId, setUser);
  return unsubscribe;
}, [userId]);

Caching Strategy
Server data: TanStack Query cache (5 minutes staleTime)

User preferences: localStorage

UI state: useState

Theme: Context API

QueryClient Configuration
// main.tsx
const queryClient = new QueryClient({
  defaultOptions: {
    queries: {
      staleTime: 1000 * 60 * 5,
      refetchOnWindowFocus: true,
      retry: 1,
    },
  },
});

React Query DevTools
Include in development

Great for debugging
import { ReactQueryDevtools } from '@tanstack/react-query-devtools';

Anti-Patterns to Avoid
❌ Fetching data directly in components without TanStack Query

❌ Calling Firebase directly in components (use repositories)

❌ Using Zustand/Redux for server state

❌ Not invalidating cache after mutations

❌ Forgetting to unsubscribe from Firestore listeners



## Coding Conventions

### 1. Component Creation
- **Use shadcn/ui** components as building blocks whenever possible
- Create new components in `src/components/custom/` with PascalCase names
- Each component should have its own folder with an `index.tsx` export
- Use **function declarations** (not arrow functions) for components:
```typescript
// ✅ Good
export function Button({ children, ...props }: ButtonProps) {
  return <button {...props}>{children}</button>;
}

// ❌ Bad
export const Button = ({ children, ...props }: ButtonProps) => {
  return <button {...props}>{children}</button>;
};
Components should have a clear responsibility (single responsibility principle)

Use React.memo() for components that render frequently with same props

2. Styling with Tailwind & shadcn/ui
Use shadcn/ui variants (e.g., variant="destructive") instead of raw Tailwind classes when available

For custom styles, use Tailwind utility classes directly

Leverage the cn() helper from @/lib/utils for conditional classes:
import { cn } from "@/lib/utils";

<div className={cn(
  "base-class",
  isActive && "active-class",
  className // Allow className prop override
)}>
For complex components, extract styles into constants or separate files

Use Tailwind's dark mode with dark: prefix when needed

Follow the design tokens defined in components.json

3. Path Aliases
Always use the @ alias for imports from the src directory:
// ✅ Good
import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button";
import { useCustomHook } from "@/hooks/use-custom-hook";
import { cn } from "@/lib/utils";

// ❌ Bad - Avoid relative paths for deep imports
import { Button } from "../../../components/ui/button";
import { useCustomHook } from "../../hooks/use-custom-hook";
State Management
Use React's built-in hooks for local state:

useState for simple state

useReducer for complex state logic

useContext for global state (with Context API)

For server state, use TanStack Query (React Query) if installed

Custom hooks should:

Be placed in src/hooks/ with use prefix

Return an object with clear, typed properties

Handle loading and error states

Avoid prop drilling - use context or custom hooks instead

5. TypeScript Guidelines
Prefer interface over type for object types that will be extended

Use explicit return types for functions:
function getUser(id: string): Promise<User> {
  // ...
}
Avoid any - use unknown and type guards when types are uncertain

Use discriminated unions for complex state management

Export types/interfaces that are used across multiple files

Use satisfies operator for literal type validation

Enable strict mode in tsconfig.json

6. File Naming Conventions
Components: PascalCase (UserProfile.tsx)

Hooks: camelCase with use prefix (useAuth.ts)

Utilities: camelCase (formatDate.ts)

Types/Interfaces: PascalCase (UserTypes.ts)

Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (API_ENDPOINTS.ts)

Page files: lowercase with hyphens (user-profile.tsx)

Test files: *.test.ts or *.spec.ts

7. React Best Practices
Use React 18 features (automatic batching, transitions, etc.)

Prefer function components with hooks over class components

Use React.memo for expensive components

Use useCallback and useMemo for expensive operations

Avoid inline function definitions in JSX props

Use key prop properly in lists (not index)

Implement error boundaries for error handling

shadcn/ui Specific Rules
Adding New Components
When adding shadcn/ui components, use:
npx shadcn@latest add <component-name>
Never manually create shadcn/ui components - always use the CLI.

Component Customization
Check if the variant API supports your customization first

If needed, wrap the component instead of modifying it directly:

export const CustomButton = ({ children, ...props }) => (
  <Button {...props} className="custom-style">
    {children}
  </Button>
);
Use the className prop for one-off style changes

For global style changes, update the theme in components.json or src/styles/globals.css

Extend shadcn/ui components with your own variants by wrapping them

Theme Colors
The project uses the neutral color palette by default. Available colors:

background, foreground (text)

primary, secondary, accent

muted, destructive, border

ring (focus rings)

chart-1 through chart-5 (for charts)

sidebar and related variables

Available shadcn/ui Components
Commonly used components:

Button, Card, Dialog, DropdownMenu

Input, Label, Select, Textarea

Table, Pagination, Tabs

Form (with React Hook Form integration)

Toast, Alert, Badge

Navigation Menu, Sidebar

Performance & Best Practices
1. Image Optimization
Use Vite's built-in image optimization

Prefer WebP/AVIF formats with fallbacks

Lazy load images with loading="lazy"

Use <picture> elements for responsive images

Set appropriate image sizes with width and height attributes

2. Bundle Size Optimization
Use dynamic imports for route-level code splitting:
const LazyComponent = React.lazy(() => import('./HeavyComponent'));
Monitor bundle size with npm run build -- --report

Use React.lazy and Suspense for code splitting

Remove unused dependencies with depcheck

Use tree-shakeable imports (e.g., import { Button } from 'lucide-react')

3. Accessibility (a11y)
Use semantic HTML elements (<button>, <nav>, <article>)

Include aria-* attributes when needed

Ensure proper focus management with shadcn/ui's built-in keyboard navigation

Maintain proper heading hierarchy (h1 > h2 > h3)

Use aria-label for icon-only buttons

Test with screen readers and keyboard navigation

Ensure sufficient color contrast ratios

4. Error Handling
Use error boundaries with fallback UI

Implement global error handler for API calls

Show user-friendly error messages

Log errors to console in development

Use try/catch blocks for async operations

5. Testing Strategy
Write unit tests for utilities and hooks

Use React Testing Library for component tests

Test user interactions and accessibility

Mock API calls in tests

Run tests with npm test

Development Workflow
Build Commands
npm run dev          # Start development server
npm run build        # Build for production
npm run preview      # Preview production build locally
npm run lint         # Run ESLint
npm run format       # Auto-format code (if Prettier configured)
npm run test         # Run tests
npm run type-check   # Run TypeScript type checking
Git Workflow
Main branch: production-ready code

Develop branch: integration branch

Feature branches: feature/feature-name

Bug fixes: fix/issue-description

Hotfixes: hotfix/issue-description

Commit Message Conventions
Follow conventional commits:

feat: New feature

fix: Bug fix

docs: Documentation changes

style: Code style changes (formatting, semicolons, etc.)

refactor: Code refactoring

test: Adding or updating tests

chore: Maintenance tasks (dependencies, configs)

perf: Performance improvements

ci: CI/CD changes

Example: feat: add user profile page with avatar upload

Code Review Guidelines
Review for functionality, performance, and accessibility

Check for proper error handling

Ensure TypeScript types are used correctly

Verify shadcn/ui components are used appropriately

Look for potential security issues

Test in different browsers and viewports

Environment Variables
# Required
VITE_API_URL=https://api.example.com

# Optional
VITE_ANALYTICS_ID=your-analytics-id
VITE_SENTRY_DSN=your-sentry-dsn
API Integration
Use environment variables for API endpoints

Implement error handling and retry logic

Use request/response interceptors for common tasks

Cache API responses when appropriate

Handle authentication tokens securely

Use optimistic updates for better UX

Security Guidelines
Sanitize user input (use DOMPurify for HTML)

Validate all user inputs on server side

Never store sensitive data in localStorage

Use HTTPS in production

Implement proper authentication and authorization

Set secure HTTP headers

Use Content Security Policy (CSP)

Documentation
Write JSDoc comments for utilities and complex logic

Maintain a README with setup instructions

Document API endpoints and data structures

Add comments for non-obvious code

Keep CHANGELOG updated

Document components with Storybook if installed

Debugging
Use React Developer Tools for component inspection

Use browser DevTools for network and performance

Add console logs only for debugging (remove before commit)

Use debugger statement sparingly

Use VS Code debugger for TypeScript debugging

Deployment
Build with npm run build

Deploy dist/ folder to hosting service

Common hosting options: Vercel, Netlify, AWS, or Cloudflare Pages

Set environment variables in hosting platform

Enable SSL/TLS for production

Configure custom domain and redirects

